# Terraform Multi-Cloud Lab

![Terraform](https://img.shields.io/badge/Terraform-IaC-7B42BC?style=for-the-badge&logo=terraform&logoColor=white)
![AWS](https://img.shields.io/badge/AWS-Cloud-232F3E?style=for-the-badge&logo=amazon-aws&logoColor=white)
![Azure](https://img.shields.io/badge/Azure-Cloud-0078D4?style=for-the-badge&logo=microsoftazure&logoColor=white)
![DevOps](https://img.shields.io/badge/DevOps-Automation-0F766E?style=for-the-badge)
![GitHub](https://img.shields.io/badge/GitHub-Portfolio-181717?style=for-the-badge&logo=github&logoColor=white)

A reusable Infrastructure as Code lab for provisioning and managing cloud resources across multiple environments using Terraform.  
This project is designed to demonstrate modular Terraform patterns, environment separation, remote state management, and deployment automation practices relevant to DevOps and cloud engineering roles.

## Overview

This repository serves as a portfolio-ready IaC project that reflects real-world cloud infrastructure workflows. It focuses on building maintainable Terraform code that can scale across environments while keeping infrastructure definitions consistent, reusable, and easy to review.

The goal is to show how infrastructure can be treated as code with clear structure, version control, and repeatable deployments.

## Project Goals

- Build reusable Terraform modules.
- Organize infrastructure by environment.
- Demonstrate scalable IaC structure.
- Show cloud provisioning workflow and best practices.
- Practice clean state management and configuration patterns.
- Create a portfolio project that reflects enterprise-style cloud automation.

## Architecture

This lab is organized around a modular Terraform approach where common infrastructure components are separated into reusable building blocks.

Typical flow:

```text
Terraform code
→ reusable modules
→ environment-specific variables
→ plan/apply workflow
→ cloud resources provisioned in AWS or Azure
```

The structure is designed to make it easier to extend the project for development, testing, and production-style environments.

## Tech Stack

- Terraform
- AWS
- Azure
- Git
- YAML

## Project Structure

```text
terraform-multi-cloud-lab/
├── modules/
│   ├── networking/
│   ├── compute/
│   ├── storage/
│   └── security/
├── environments/
│   ├── dev/
│   ├── qa/
│   └── prod/
├── scripts/
├── docs/
└── README.md
```

## Workflow

1. Define infrastructure requirements.
2. Build reusable Terraform modules.
3. Configure environment-specific variables.
4. Run `terraform plan` to validate changes.
5. Apply infrastructure changes safely.
6. Review and update as the environment evolves.

This workflow demonstrates how Infrastructure as Code can support repeatable delivery and reduce configuration drift.

## Key Features

- Modular Terraform design.
- Environment-based configuration.
- Infrastructure provisioning using code.
- Cloud-neutral project structure that can support AWS and Azure.
- Portfolio-friendly layout for recruiters and hiring managers.
- Foundation for adding CI/CD pipeline automation later.

## Example Use Cases

- Provision a cloud environment for application deployment.
- Create separate dev, QA, and prod infrastructure stacks.
- Standardize networking, storage, and compute setup.
- Demonstrate Terraform-based automation in a cloud engineering portfolio.

## How to Run

```bash
terraform init
terraform plan
terraform apply
```

If you use environment folders, run the commands from the target environment directory.

## Future Improvements

- Add remote state storage.
- Add variable validation and input constraints.
- Add CI/CD pipeline integration.
- Add more reusable modules.
- Expand monitoring and security controls.
- Add diagrams and screenshots for the architecture.

## Why This Project Matters

This project shows practical cloud engineering skills beyond basic Terraform syntax. It demonstrates how to structure infrastructure for reuse, maintainability, and scale — which is exactly what DevOps and cloud teams want to see in a portfolio.

